segments.text: This is an interview with Jane Gregory by Molly Aldrich on November 17, 1990 at her home concerning the Civil Rights Movement in the 60s.
Could you please state your name for us?
Jane Gregory.
Could you tell us when you were born?
In 1951 in Houston, Texas.
And could you give us a little bit of background on your education?
Well, being born in Houston in 1951 in a white family meant you lived on the southeast side of town over off Scott Street and in the University of Houston area.
But in the 60s, the great white flight took off for southwest Houston.
I remember when the first black family bought a home on our block.
It was like the Purcell sons went up overnight.
And I ended up
in Bel Air High School.
Well, I went to junior high and elementary school on the southwest side too, but I graduated from Bel Air High School in 1969 and then started the University of Texas in the fall of 69.
Why did you become involved in the Civil Rights Movement?
I guess
Early on, I had a very clear idea of the fact that I lived in a prejudiced family.
Maybe not prejudiced by Southern standards, but somehow prejudiced by my own standards.
We had what my mother referred to as a negra maid.
My mother thought that was very liberal of her to use that particular word.
But she didn't eat lunch with us at our table.
And I remember questioning my mom about that even really early.
But I guess the thing that triggered the civil rights movement big time for me was the election year of 1968, when George Wallace and Curtis LeMay were running on the American Party ticket.
And they were, as most people of my generation will remember, very
outspoken for the rights and very down on any type of integration.
And to make matters worse, my father had fought with Curtis LeMay during World War II and strongly supported the Wallace LeMay ticket.
So while he was nailing up campaign signs and posting them in our front yard, I went to the other extreme.
I suppose a way of not only supporting a cause I believed in, but also rebelling against those authoritarian ties that everybody needs to rebel against.
What influenced your decision to join the Students for a Democratic Society?
Well, there were several campus groups at the time.
I was involved at first with just general peace marches.
Now, the peace marches were primarily against the Vietnam War.
Civil rights was sort of just a splinter of it.
The big thing was the Vietnam War because it affected so many people my age.
And it did not seem that the passive resistance was working at all.
and that a more direct and perhaps more violent tactic was needed.
And I listened to a lot of the Chicago 7 trials, and I had involvements with people who were in California and Oregon and on the West Coast and persuaded me that
the SDS would be the only way we could affect the change.
How many were in the UT chapter and what years were you involved in it?
I was only in it for one year in 1969.
By 70, I had become so disillusioned.
with the United States in general that I left the country.

But in the UT chapter, at the time, now I don't know how many card-carrying SDS members there were, but I know of at least 200 active, active people that I could call at any time with any crazy idea or plot or any type of...
anarchist idea that would cause or disrupt normal campus activities to a point that we could make our point.
What was your view on American involvement in Vietnam?
I was totally opposed.
And I had two cousins fighting in that particular war, and my family was extremely
agitated with me for being involved.

The civil rights movement had been bad enough, but to march against the government of the United States and to go on to the Capitol grounds, there was a big protest march that we were involved in where the students attempted to take over the state Capitol.
And that was my first experience with tear gas, a very pleasant one.
And Lyndon Johnson, being from Texas, I guess even insulted them more that I would be against the war.
But total opposition to the war is the only way I can express it.
I felt it was morally wrong, and I felt that people were dying over there for no just reason.
I didn't feel like the United States had any business in Vietnam.
Friends in SDS and other groups had said that Cambodia was next on the list, and they were sure right about that.
To answer your question, I was totally opposed.
How many other organizations were you involved with during the 60s movement?
When you belong to SDS, first of all, you didn't go around announcing particularly that you were in SDS because it could get you in a whole lot of trouble.
So there was a different group that was much more peaceful in nature.
It was a University of Texas group.
I'm trying to remember the name.
Goodness gracious.
Well, Students Against the Vietnam War or Students Opposed to the Vietnam War.
I can't remember the initial or the acronym for it, but I was involved in that.
But most of the other groups that I became involved in, I did it just to shield my membership in SDS because I didn't...
If I was associated with more peaceful groups and active in a few of the more peaceful demonstrations, I never missed a demonstration.
And at the time, college professors were most understanding.
I'd say the majority of the faculty in all of the classes I took, my professors were against the Vietnam War.
I spent very little time in class, actually, the first semester at the University of Texas.
But you could get credit if you went to the peace marches and marched with your professors, and I was there.
It was a lot more fun than studying anthropology.
What types of demonstrations were you involved in, and could you explain the different ones?
Well, the one I mentioned earlier, the largest demonstration I suppose I was ever involved in was the
the march onto the state capitol grounds.
And there were thousands of students there, literally thousands.
And I'm not sure at what point we marched from the campus to the capitol building.
And there were police the whole way along, but they didn't seem, they were there and they were policing the crowds.
but they did not seem really concerned.
We joked around with them a lot.
We kidded with them a lot, like, come on, join us, and they'd give you the peace sign, and you'd flash it back, and we'd pass construction workers and people on the way and just kid around.
There was none of the angriness that you sometimes see where,
construction workers would get in confrontations with students or scream about communists or anything like that.
It was such a mild day.
I remember that most about it.
And there were a lot of speeches on the Capitol grounds by various speakers.
And I'm not sure exactly at what point it was decided that
or who was speaking that encouraged us to literally try to take over the Capitol building.
But that appealed to a great number of people I was particularly standing there with, including my psychology professor.
And so we literally went into the rotunda of the State Capitol building in an attempt to take over the State Capitol building.
Now, being young and not real clear on the idea, I'm not sure what we thought that would accomplish in retrospect.
I do know that that's when the day turned ugly because that's when the police were ordered in and tear gas was thrown in and a number of us were arrested.
I was arrested and was taken down to the Austin jail where we spent the night away singing peace songs, you know, we shall overcome.
All we were saying is give peace a chance.
Having a great old time.
My parents, however, did not look at this as a good time when they arrived in Austin to get me out of jail.
Other demonstrations, I went to Atlanta for one demonstration, and I went to New Orleans for another demonstration.
The one in Atlanta was a civil rights, and the one in New Orleans was a...
meeting of planning committees for SDS and what we could do on college campuses, and it was not a publicized meeting.
But while there, we were on the LSU campus, and we did meet with various other people.
There was another meeting out in Berkeley that year, but I was not able to go to California.
California, the West Coast was a hotbed for SDS activity, and I did communicate by letter with various people involved in that.
But I did not make the Berkeley meeting that year, which proved to be the one I should have made as far as a lot of things going on and happening.
What makes your generation different from your parents' generation?
I guess my generation was different because we not only questioned the government.
We didn't just sit back on the porch and complain about taxes.
We took to the streets and let the government know that we were really pissed off.
That this just wasn't going to fly.
That they no longer had the...
Authority, in our estimation, are the right to determine who would die and who would live a good life.
A lot's been made of the generation gap, and it wasn't a gap.
It was the Grand Canyon.
I watched my friends and myself, those years with our families,
were horrible.

I don't remember a single dinner when I would go home or at the holidays that wasn't disrupted by a huge family fight and ended with me storming out or my mother in tears or my father cursing and ranting and raving.
I mean, everything from the length of my brother's hair, you know, on that kind of trivial manner to the politics that
that children that he felt he had raised and given every opportunity, and we were turning on them.
We were throwing out all their ideals.
God was dead.
No respect for schools or teachers, certainly no respect for parents, no respect for the American flag or the American way.
He felt, my father, my mother, that we were just doomed for communism.
Women didn't wear bras.
Guys let their hair grow down their backs.
People were on drugs.
This is how my parents saw it.
They saw it on a very superficial level.
And the more they carried on, the more we did, too.
And the louder my father got, the more Archie Bunkerish, I suppose, he became.
the more he drove me into knowing I didn't want to be like him, nothing like him.
I didn't want to be like my mother.
I didn't want to be under a husband's thumb.
I wouldn't do that.
And as a result, I became a very judgmental person of my parents' generation, just as judgmental of them as they were of me because I was so determined not to end up like them.
My generation protested en masse.
We got together on that.
We were convinced that you couldn't just accept your government and think they were always right.
My father, when he went into World War II,
He went in because those goddamn Japanese snuck over there and did that to us.
He went over there.
He honestly believed he was fighting for the protection of democracy and to guarantee his children an American way of life, whereas it was a sham.
It was just to make the rich even richer.
And the thought that he just fell for that and couldn't see through what the government was doing just amazed me.
I think my generation was better educated, more analytical.
But my parents were probably more innocent and more happy, that generation.
Even though they'd been through a depression and a world war, they thought they had suffered and now that they were living a good life and they couldn't understand why we just didn't
and sit back and enjoy the fruits of their labor.
And OK, the Vietnam War was here, and the young men had to go fight.
But that was nothing that their fathers hadn't been willing to do.
And I had another cousin, two cousins in the Vietnam War, and one cousin who went to Canada.
That cousin was totally ostracized from the family.
It was his name.
His own mother struck his name out of the family Bible.
Didn't forgive him.
until amnesty was granted years later.
And once the country forgave him, I guess she thought she could too.
We were motivated by something that wasn't motivating our parents, I suppose.
The American way didn't seem like such a big motivator to us.
We were looking for a different way.
What were some of the ways your organizations went about getting their message across or mobilizing support?
Well, the demonstrations were big.
And you would put signs up all over campus announcing big demonstrations and peace marches.
And you'd bring in speakers.
Jerry Rubin, we brought in Lawrence Ferlinghetti,
a poet at the time out in California.
He still is a poet.
To read controversial poems at the time, any poem that had the word fuck in it was just considered wonderful, even if its poetic merits were nil.
But it was such a controversial time.
The word has lost some of its impact, but at the time to have a

an adult stand up in a public place and read a poem with that kind of word in it, especially if it was referred to as the fucking Vietnam War, then, you know, you could be assured that that speaker would get a rousing ovation and cheers.
SDS would use these peace marches or demonstrations a lot of times because so many people would be off campus to do, when I look back on it, it's probably more practical jokes than anything.
Although it was disruptive at the time, they would cut phone wires in the administration building.
They would go around and jam locks
to major doors so that people couldn't get in to their offices or buildings.
That seemed to be one of their favorites.
Flag burnings were another way that you could always draw a big crowd along with draft burning
And everybody would just come, and the guys would have their draft cards, and it'd just take a couple of them to start throwing them in there.
And the next thing you know, you'd have a pretty good fire.
I guess another way support was gathered was through drugs.
And marijuana was a big drug at the time, along with LSD, but...
He knew if somebody had pot and joints started passing around, he knew that more people would probably end up burning their draft cards that night than might have otherwise.
So it was always good to keep drugs and take drugs to these marches.
Everybody smoked marijuana, and by everybody I mean everybody I knew or had anything in common with, my professors, my friends, people that I'd known to be perfectly quote unquote straight people.
Music was another way of getting support.
Janis Joplin was big at the time.
The Beatles started getting really big into the peace movement.
You'd blare these records on huge speakers across the campus,
start passing around a joint or two, and the next thing you knew, you were willing to march again wherever people wanted to go.
So you think.
At the flag burnings, this is when hostility sometimes would come out between the community and the campus because a lot of people have very strong feelings about the flag.

When the flag would be burned, sometimes there would be somebody who would rush in and try to yank it out of a fire or start screaming at people who were doing it and the name calling would begin and everything.
But these people were really few, very few and hard between.
And I don't suppose any discussion at this time of different things that people did at this time would be complete without at least mentioning sex.
And I guess sex was another way we really had of motivating people because the free love, that Haight-Ashbury summer and everything became a real focal point.
And it was neat to be in the group I was in because you could have
You could have many different sexual partners and enjoy sex, and certainly the stigmatism was off it.
It wasn't like only bad girls did that or only tramps did that.
I mean, it was part of the movement.
It was free love, and it was considered cool, and you could do that and not have a name on you.
And at the time, I really believed that having sex with someone was nothing more than just an extension of friendship and a sharing of common goals and bonds.
And this was a person, certainly I didn't intend to marry, but that we shared that particular experience and mix in the drugs and the sex.
And you attracted a lot of young men to your movement.
I mean, think about it.
You're 18, 19 years old.
You're away from home for the first time.
The girls are all into this peace stuff and with it comes drugs and sex.
Seemed pretty good.
Kent State was a big mobilizing factor when the National Guard was called in and students were actually killed on a college campus by the National Guardsmen.
And that became a real focal point of how bad things had gotten in the country when now we had
guardsmen firing on college students who were actually exercising their right to express their opinions, freedom of speech.
It tore the country apart, Kent State.
It brought everything to a head here.
It's one thing to send your son off to the Vietnam War where you know the likelihood that he'll be killed is great, but to send your sons and daughters to school
and have the National Guard, who, let's face it, your tax dollars were going to support, fire upon your children.
That brought a lot of parental support to the side of the peace movement.
How do you feel the music affected your generation?
Oh.
Well, I don't feel as strongly as Plato did that.
Music must be controlled, or as Aristotle did, that music must be censored.
But I do think it had a profound effect.
The music seemed perfectly geared to what we were fighting about and what we were trying to push, the civil rights ideas.
He ain't heavy.
He's my brother.
The idea of free love.
and drugs and goodness.
It just went hand in hand with the movement of the time.
Woodstock in the summer of 1969, the summer after I graduated from high school, my parents refused to let me go, would not let us go.
Threatened me with everything in the world if I went, so of course I went.
My best friend Colleen and I and one other girl told our parents, asked our parents, we told them, whatever, we were going to the beach.
And that night, we called from Atlanta just to say we were going.
And I'll never forget, my father said, I said, he said, why aren't you home?
And I said, I'm not coming home.
I'm in Atlanta.
We're going to Woodstock.
And he said, like hell.
And I just hung up and kept going.

And I guess that was pretty much my... That was a particularly awakening experience for a little Texas bush popper from Texas out here, because I'd never been out of the state of Texas across that infamous Mason-Dixon line at any rate.
And now I was up in what my parents refer to as Yankee territory, God knows.
And...
It was a rainy, it was cold to me, and I got very sick there, but I loved every minute of it.
I loved the fact that people could, the music just seemed to be able to make people totally lose themselves.
For the first time, I saw the real power of music and how you could just totally get in to it and just not care about anything else that was going on around you.
Of course, there were a lot of drugs there.
And it seemed that drugs were not expensive at all.
People were selling heads of acid for a buck or two bucks.
And you could get, oh gosh, you could get an ounce of marijuana for, you could get an ounce of marijuana for 30, oh gosh, less than 30, 20, 15, depending on what.
A lot of times you didn't have to pay for it at all.
You just sat there and somebody would pass you around the joint and
it would go on, but to get back to the music issue, the music was drug-oriented in a lot of ways.

Lucy in the Sky of Diamonds, of course, being the big LSD song of the time, and Janis Joplin, and me and Bobby McGee, and gosh, the Yellow Submarine, the whole idea that music was a fantastic voyage into the imagination, and
Music was the prompt, I suppose, and we used it every chance we got.
It was another way of rebelling against figures of authority because they really saw this music as detrimental.
And it was anti-American to a large extent.
It was peace movement songs, anti-war songs, pro-choice, pro-drug, free love.
Of course, that's all parents needed to hear to be turned off by it.
Did you partake in drug use?
Mm-hmm, certainly.
Which drugs did you use, and what were your reasons for using them?
I smoked a lot of marijuana.
That was primarily the only drug I did.
What were my reasons?
Well, it was a way of... At the time, to turn down a joint that was passed to you in a demonstration would be like saying, no, I don't believe in this.
I don't believe in any of this.
Marijuana was like the common bond.
It was like...
I don't know, to compare it to two soldiers in a foxhole sharing a cigarette.
It was another way of saying, I'm in this movement.
My identification is with the peace movement, the civil rights movement, and with drugs.
I believe everybody has a right to determine if they want to smoke it or not.
It was another way of saying...
hell no to the government.
You're not going to impose this limit on me.
You have no right to tell me this is illegal.
Acid, I really didn't get into.
I tried it once or twice in college and didn't like being that out of it.
Marijuana seemed to focus things in for me, and acid seemed to totally remove me from them.
And I didn't want to be totally removed.
I wanted to have things

I wanted, marijuana seemed to let me get really deep into my thoughts, and acid seemed to put me on another, or LSD seemed to put me in another area of thought, into a hallucinogenic world that I didn't really enjoy.
I didn't want to leave this world, I just wanted to kind of make it mellower, because life at that time was not mellow.
unless you were high, because otherwise you were so worried and so concerned about who you knew might be called to the Vietnam War next.
Your black friends were always on your case.

Either the Black Panther movement, which was anti-righting no matter what you tried to do or work with, and they really felt that all whites were their enemies, or your friends in the civil rights movement, black friends,
were involving you and making you put your butt on the line with them somewhere.
I remember once with a group of blacks, we all went skinny dipping and it was done at a time

that the media had been notified that we would be there at Hamilton's pool outside of Austin skinny dipping and it was done so that they would be called in and and just show a lot of white girls and black guys frolicking around having a good time totally nude and of course you know that sort of picture that gets released or I think it was in the campus newspaper
It just sent shivers down the backs of parents who envisioned all these mulatto babies.
But marijuana just helped make it seem just a little bit more mellow for a moment rather than so tense all the time.
Did you regard yourself as a hippie?
Hippie was a word used by the press and by the parents.
No, I didn't regard myself as a hippie.
A hippie was a flip word.
It was like beatnik.
It was a word that stupid TV shows got a hold of and tried to stick on us.
Hippie was so flippant.
It was like trying to ridicule or make fun of
what we were all about, I felt.

To say hippie, it made it sound like you were just some long-haired freak who stayed stoned most of the time and had no political or social conscience, which is, I think, what shows like Laugh-In and people like Goldie Hawn sort of reduced the movement to, at least on the public television channels or the public airwaves.
It would be like...
Asking someone...
I guess it would be like asking a fundamentalist Baptist if he considered himself a holy roller.
He would probably take offense at that term.
It's just one of those cutesy little titles that gets stuck on someone.
But as far as a hippie, my family certainly regarded me as a hippie.
They regarded all of my friends as hippies.
But...
Hippie was not a popular term with the movement itself.
It was one of those media terms that gets stuck on people.
What did you call yourself?
Did you have a word to describe?
No, not really.
We just considered ourselves involved with the peace movement.
My father would call us peaceniks sometimes.
And that seemed closer than hippie to me.
I just regarded myself as a free thinker and somebody who was not going to accept all the garbage that the government was trying to force down my throat.
I didn't want to get caught up in that.
But I guess if I really look back on it, I guess more than anything, we were anarchists.
We were people who wanted to bring about an overthrow of the government.
We were people who wanted to bring about an overthrow of the system.
And by system, I mean the family system, the way most people regarded the education system.
We wanted everything to be run on a whole different basis that involved no censorship.
Everybody could just, quote unquote, do their own thing.
How do you feel about the statement that you, along with other SDS members, were communist sympathizers?
I can live with that.
To me, calling someone a communist is not an insult.
That does not make you a bad person to me.
I'm not sure what they meant by communist sympathizers.
I'm not even sure that most people who use the word communist have any idea of
the word as far as a communist, a pure theoretical look at the communist belief that it's a society that works for the mutual benefits of other people.
If they want to call me a communist sympathizer, that's fine with me.
I think the word was erroneously used to mean a sympathizer or to have some sort of Russian ties.
And I didn't know much about Russia at the time.
Communal living was a big thing at the time.
I knew several people who did live in communes.
I had friends in Tennessee that lived on a commune that still works today called The Farm.
I had lots of friends out in California and Oregon who lived on communes.
And the fact that if someone thought
To say that I was a communist sympathizer, I knew no more about the communist government and what was going on over there.
And what I did know, it seemed to me that it was somewhat of a repressive government.
So I would have never supported that.
I think they threw that term out because the worst thing you could be at the time was somebody who supported Russian or communism.
I mean, the Red Scare and Joseph McCarthy were still very much alive in a lot of people's minds.
And...
To say that you were a communist sympathizer meant that you were just totally opposed to a democratic way of life.
And that got the conservative side all in an uproar because now they could look at anybody with long hair or faded jeans or people who spoke out against the war.
They didn't listen to what those people had to say.
because the conservative element, the political element, had branded us as communist sympathizers.
So they no longer heard the words.
They just thought of us as communist, which was an automatic turn off.
It was a clever way of branding us.
It would effectively
make anything we had to say not worth listening to if the people that we were trying to get to thought we were communists.
It would be like if I told you this person was a child molester.
I mean, are you really going to listen to them tell you how to bring up your children?
What interesting public figures did you meet during your years in the SDS?
What type of people?
I guess I met some famous people, enough to shake hands with them on the podium and be introduced to them, like Abby Hoffman and Jerry Rubin.
I did meet Lawrence Forland Getty when he was in Texas.
I heard Timothy Leary speak, but I'd never actually met him.
I heard... Oh...
various people associated with the Black Panther Movement and Malcolm X and the Civil Rights Movement, you know.
But I met Jane Fonda on one occasion, who my father just thought that was horrible, that I would even shake her hand.
But those people didn't impress me nearly as much as my college professors at the time.
One in particular, my psychology professor, Devendra Singh, who I think had a big influence on just how I felt.
I mean, immediately he was so anti-Vietnam War.
And he introduced me to such a different way of looking at the world.
And he was an Indian.
And of course, that didn't sit well with my parents either.
But we had a relationship for the year.
And I greatly respected him and his views.
And my English professor, I was in an experimental English class that year.
And boy, was it Peter Botsworth.
He was another real popular speaker at the time on the University of Texas campus.
These people would invite you into their homes, and you really felt a great deal of care and concern from these people.
They were much more important to me than any of the big names.
What was your parents' reaction to your behavior in college or your involvement with the STFs?
Well, it was not a good time.
My father literally came up to the University of Texas one night.
He got into Austin about 10 o'clock on a day that they had filmed

us in various activities on this particular day we had been protesting the cutting down of trees along barton creek and we'd actually chained ourselves to trees and the bulldozers had come and wouldn't chop down the trees and the police with the bull horns and everything but my father had seen it on the six o'clock news and he immediately jumped in his car and announced to my mother that he was not going to support a goddamn commie

You know, he'd be up there in Austin, and he came, and unfortunately he came, and my psychology professor Devendra and I were, we were actually just sitting in the living room at the time, but I think we were in various stages of undress.
And my father, who was a little man, I mean, he was maybe 5'8", 5'9", and Devendra was tall.
He was 6'1".
My father literally threw him up against the wall and then pushed him down the stairs, yelling and screaming the whole time.

Well, being Miss Peace Love that I was, I wasn't going to call the police, but I did tell my father to leave and ordered him off, and he threatened to cut me off financially, and I told him that was fine with me.
Knowing full well he probably wouldn't do it.
Things were very strained at this time.
My family did not know...
of how much I was involved in SDS.

And if they had known that I was actually perpetrating any of the vandalism or the disrupting of services on the campus, they would have had... Well, I did so many things that I thought they would disown me for, but...
I think more than anything, the fact that I dated people that were not of the same race and religion, and or religion, had them floored.
They just lived in fear that I would take off with somebody God knows who.
It was very strange.
It was very difficult.
They were very, very unhappy.
Totally unsupportive of any views I had.
They couldn't support them.
And even a financial cutoff wasn't a big threat because everything was so anti-materialistic at the time.
Student loans were easily available.

You could live very cheaply in Austin, and you could live with friends, and I never had to do that, but I had a number of people stay with me for weeks at a time, and that was just considered cool then, even though sometimes you would get a little hacked, but whoever was staying with you wasn't exactly picking up after him or herself.
You would never say too much about it.
You would probably just get high and try to forget it.
